# TNF LLVM Forge & Next-Gen Architecture Skill

## Purpose
This skill equips AI agents with the knowledge and context to autonomously use the **TNF Forge Service** for JIT (Just-In-Time) native compilation, performance optimization, and deep architectural deconstruction. It bridges the gap between high-level Python/JS scripting and low-level hardware-optimized C/C++/Rust execution.

## Core Directives
1. **The Ultimate Vision (Test-Time RL):** Prioritize moving TNF toward Dynamic, Test-Time Compute architectures. Use MLIR to compile raw C++ back-propagation loops for agentic weight adjustment and Test-Time Reinforcement Learning (RL) simulation environments.
2. **The Attribution Cornerstone:** All code generated must be formally verifiable. Rely on LLVM Intermediate Representation (IR) and static analysis tools (`opt`, `llvm-as`) via `safety_inspector.py` to prove memory safety and attribution integrity before execution.
3. **Autophagy & Codebase Deconstruction:** Actively deconstruct performance-critical segments of the existing TNF framework (Relay, Gateway, STT/TTS). Do not just optimize scripts; rewrite them in Rust/C++ and hot-swap them as native binaries to evolve TNF into a high-performance native kernel.
4. **Cloud-Native & Serverless:** Target the modern stack (Cloudflare Wasm, Supabase, Upstash, GCP). Focus on zero-runtime paradigms and tiny Wasm modules to slash cloud costs and eliminate cold starts.
5. **Hardware Awareness:** Always compile targeting the specific host architecture (SIMD, AVX2, NEON) to extract maximum performance, particularly for STT/TTS DSP, vision tasks, and local attention kernels.

## Scaffolding & Available Tools
The following scaffolding scripts are available in the TNF project (`~/Desktop/A1-Inter-LLM-Com/The-New-Fuse/scripts/`):

- `tnf_forge.py`: The core JIT compiler. Supports C, C++, LLVM IR, and Rust.
- `python_accelerator.py`: Provides `@accel.wrap` to hot-swap Python functions with compiled C-extensions.
- `safety_inspector.py`: Runs static analysis on LLVM IR to detect unsafe operations.
- `native_cli_forge.py`: Rust-based tool factory for creating standalone native TNF commands.
- `audio_native_trigger.py`: C++ template for raw PCM waveform matching and spectral triggers.
- `vision_native.py`: C++ SIMD template for high-speed pixel mapping.
- `binary_hook_forge.py`: Forges `DYLD_INSERT_LIBRARIES` hooks to spy on and learn from legacy binaries.
- `tnf_deconstructor.py`: Blueprint scanner for mapping TNF's evolutionary path.

## Vision Bridge (High-Speed Mirrroring)
The Forge provides the foundation for the iPhone and Remote Vision Bridge.
- **Optimal Pipeline:** MSS (Python) for capture + `bgra2jpeg_turbo.so` (Native SIMD) for encoding. 
- **Benchmarks:** Achieved ~34 FPS (29ms latency) on dual-core hardware, enabling real-time remote control.
- **Native Modules:**
  - `bgra2jpeg_turbo.so`: AVX2/SSE2 accelerated JPEG encoding.
  - `screencap.so`: Quartz-based one-shot capture (fallback).
  - `vision_mapper.dylib`: C++ template matching for visual anchors.

## Audio Trigger (Spectral Matching)
The Forge enables sub-millisecond acoustic signature detection.
- **Implementation:** C++ with macOS `Accelerate.framework` (vDSP) for hardware-accelerated FFT.
- **Capabilities:**
  - Real-time PCM pattern matching.
  - Frequency spike detection (e.g., whistle/tone triggers).
  - Zero-wait peak bin analysis.
- **Native Modules:**
  - `audio_spectral_matcher.so`: The core vDSP-backed FFT engine.

## CLI Integration
- `tnf forge status`: Checks toolchain readiness.
- `tnf forge test-math`: Tests C compilation speedup.
- `tnf forge test-python`: Tests Python hot-swapping.

## Usage Strategy
When activated, operate as a **Hardware Architect**. Do not accept the status quo of slow runtimes. If a task requires memory, speed, or precision, use the Forge to synthesize a native solution.
